      "uiColor": "red",
      "title": "Quick question first…",
      "question": "A heavy lorry and a light car are both moving at the same speed. Which has more momentum?",
      "options": [
        "The car - it’s faster for its size",
        "They have the same momentum",
        "The lorry, it has more mass",
        "It depends on the road surface"
      ],
      "correctIndex": 2,
      "misconceptionFeedback": "⚠️ Common misconception! Momentum depends on both mass and velocity: p = mv. Since both are travelling at the same speed (same v), the object with the greater mass has the greater momentum. Road surface has no effect on momentum, only on friction.",
      "correctFeedback": "✓ Correct! Momentum p = mv, so with the same velocity, the lorry’s larger mass gives it a greater momentum. This is why lorries are much harder to stop than cars at the same speed."
    },
    {
      "id": "concept",
      "type": "concept",
      "uiTag": "Concept",
      "uiColor": "blue",
      "title": "Momentum",
      "bodyHTML": "<strong>Momentum</strong> equals <strong>mass × velocity</strong>, measured in <strong>kg m/s</strong>. Momentum is a <strong>vector</strong>: it has both size and direction. In any collision (or explosion), <strong>total momentum is conserved</strong>: the total before equals the total after, provided no external forces act.",
      "keyEquation": "p = m × v",
      "diagram": {
